La Nina at a glance


"La Nina means, for Australia, an increased risk of rainfall - particularly in the central, eastern and northern parts of the country."
Dr. Andrew Watkins
Head of Long-Range forecasting - BoM

Australia in La Nina : A glimpse into the past

2010 2012

Impact: STRONG

2011 and 2010 were the second (2011 at 708 mm) andthird (2010 at 703 mm) wettest calendar years onrecord for Australia, both well above the long-term average of 465 mm.

The 2010 – 2012 La Nina event saw two peaks over successive summers, with the 2010 – 2011 peak being one of the strongest on record. In October 2010 and December 2010, as well as February 2011 and March 2011, the monthly Southern Oscillation Index values were the highest on record.

The 2011 – 2012 peak on the other end was relatively weaker, but still had moderately strong atmospheric and oceanic indicators. Combined, the two events yielded Australia’s wettest 24-month period – from April 2010 to March 2012) on record, as well as the wettest two-calendar-year period (2010-2012) with 1411mm of rainfall (topping the previous record of 1407mm in 1973-1974)

Flooding was widespread between September 2010 and March 2011.

Southeast Queensland saw severe flooding, along with large areas of northern and western Victoria, New South Wales northwestern Western Australia, and eastern Tasmania having been subjected to significant flooding.

Concerning was the widespread flooding across southeast Australia that resulted in a significant increase in mosquito-borne diseases, with 1092 cases ofRoss River Virusbeing detected in Victoria between January and April, and 151 cases ofBarmah Forest Virus.

Much of inland southerns and far northernQueensland, most of New South Wales, northernVictoria and central Australia experienced flooding at least one between late November 2011 and March 2012.

Notable tropical cyclones occurring during this period includeYasi,Carlos,GrantandLua

2008 2009

Impact : WEAK – MODERATE

This period saw aweaker, shorter, more marginal occurrence of La Nina – with its greatest impactoccurring across the north of Australia during the period August 2008 to April 2009.

ItEgan with close-to-average rainfall recorded predominantly over the northern regions of the country during August 2008 to October 2008 and below to very-much-below-average rainfall in the southeast. This was then followed by a widespread wet November 2008 to December 2008 with 62% of Australia recording much-above-average rainfall.

It was during the same period that Western Australia underwent the tropical cyclone Billy, which reflected in the highest record falls duringDecember in the region surrounding Wyndham inthe Northern Territory.

2007 2008

Impact : WEAK – MODERATE

Moderate impact for the nine months fromJune 2007 – February 2008 wasexperience in Australia during thisparticular cycle of La Nina. The Pattern saw moreanomalousbehavior in terms of below-average falls from central to southeastern Australia, largely due to the very dry conditions fromAugust 2007 to October 2007.

June 2007 in fact brought above average rainfall, includinglarge areas withrecord high falls across most of central and eastern regions.

Wet conditions also extended down the east coast where numerous floods occurred in New South Wales and in Gippsland.

More typical La Nina rainfall anomalies took hold from November 2007 – February 2008being moderately wet through the east of the mainland, and theother fo both theNorthern Territory andWestern Australia. A few small regions in Queensland and New South Wales had the highest-on-record falls for the four month period.

1998 2001

Impact : STRONG

With an Australian-wide average of 698 mm, the calendar year 2000 was observed to be the second wettest year since 1900 (following 760mm in 1974)

Although at varied levels of intensity, May 1998 – March 2001 could be considered a long La Nina phase as experienced in Australia.

The country saw moderate to strong effects in different parts, from 97% of someregions being exposed to record high rainfalls.

As the pattern included a transition towards a neutral state in time, followed by the resurgence of La Nina conditions succeeding the onset of the northern wet season which brought with it widespread rainfalls over most of the country for eight months fromOctober 1999 to may 2000. It recurred once moreduring the period from October 2000 to 2001.
